AWS services overview
•	AWS offers a wide range of cloud services across categories like compute, storage, database, analytics, networking, security, mobile apps, IoT, and machine learning.
•	Service names often indicate their function, e.g., Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (compute), Amazon Simple Storage Service (storage), Amazon Relational Database Service (database).
•	Some services are named after the open source technology they manage, such as Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Kubernetes) and Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Elasticsearch).
•	AWS fully manages these services, handling server maintenance, patching, and scaling, so you can focus on building your applications.
•	Understanding service categories and naming conventions helps in quickly identifying the right AWS service for specific needs, which is useful for both practical use and exam preparation.
AWS compute services:
•	Compute Service Types: AWS offers virtual machines (Amazon EC2), serverless (AWS Lambda), and orchestration services (AWS Batch, AWS Elastic Beanstalk).

•	Amazon EC2: Virtual servers you can customize (OS, CPU, storage) with shared responsibility—AWS manages hardware and virtualization; you manage OS and data.

•	AWS Lambda: Serverless computing where AWS fully manages servers; you upload code (functions) and pay only for compute time used. Supports multiple programming languages.

•	AWS Batch: Orchestrates batch computing workloads by dynamically provisioning EC2 instances based on job requirements, removing the need to manage batch software.

•	AWS Elastic Beanstalk: Automates deployment and management of applications, handling provisioning, scaling, and monitoring, while allowing access to underlying EC2 instances.

•	Amazon LightSail: Simplified virtual private server solution with predictable pricing and easy resource management.

•	AWS Outposts: Hybrid service delivering AWS infrastructure to your on-premises data center for consistent cloud experience.


These notes capture the essence of AWS compute services covered and their use cases, helping you understand their differences and applications.

AWS container services module:
•	Containers vs Virtual Machines: Containers emulate applications and their dependencies without virtualizing the entire OS, making them lightweight compared to virtual machines which emulate entire computers.

•	Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service): A scalable container orchestration service supporting Docker containers. It manages clusters and tasks, can run on AWS Fargate (serverless) or EC2 instances, and integrates with AWS services for storage, security, and scaling.

•	Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service): A fully managed Kubernetes service for running containerized workloads. It supports running pods on Fargate or EC2 and is cloud-agnostic, allowing easier migration across environments.

•	AWS Fargate: A serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to manage servers. It runs ECS tasks or EKS pods in isolated environments and charges based on resources used.

•	Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry): A managed Docker container registry integrated with ECS for storing and deploying container images securely.

•	Additional Tools: AWS App2Container helps modernize .NET and Java apps into containers, while AWS Copilot automates deployment and management of containerized applications.
AWS storage services module:
•	Amazon EC2 Instance Store: Temporary block-level storage physically attached to the host server. Ideal for ephemeral data like caches or buffers. Data is lost when the instance stops or terminates.

•	Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS): Persistent block storage for EC2 instances. Data persists through instance stops/restarts. Supports SSD and HDD volumes with different performance profiles (IOPS vs throughput). Volumes are zonal and can be encrypted.

•	Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3): Object storage with virtually unlimited capacity. Stores data as objects in buckets. Multiple storage classes for different access patterns (Standard, Intelligent-Tiering, Infrequent Access, Glacier for archiving). Features include lifecycle policies, versioning, replication, and security controls.

•	Amazon S3 Glacier: Low-cost archival storage for rarely accessed data with longer retrieval times. Has retrieval options (Expedited, Standard, Bulk). Minimum storage durations apply.

•	Amazon Elastic File System (EFS): Scalable shared file storage for Linux EC2 instances using NFS. Supports Standard and Infrequent Access classes with lifecycle policies.

•	Amazon FSx for Lustre: High-performance shared file system for Linux, optimized for HPC and machine learning workloads needing fast parallel storage.

•	Amazon FSx for Windows Server: Fully managed Windows file server supporting SMB protocol and Active Directory integration for Windows workloads.

•	AWS Backup: Managed backup service to automate backups of servers and databases with customizable retention and lifecycle policies.

•	AWS Storage Gateway: Hybrid cloud storage connecting on-premises storage to AWS. Includes File Gateway (NFS/SMB to S3), Volume Gateway (block storage with snapshots), and Tape Gateway (virtual tape library).

AWS purpose-built databases:

•	Relational Databases (ACID properties): Amazon RDS and Amazon Aurora support atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability to ensure data integrity.
•	Amazon RDS: Managed relational database service supporting multiple engines (MySQL, Postgres, Oracle, etc.), with options for single AZ or multi-AZ deployments for high availability.
•	Amazon Aurora: AWS-owned relational database compatible with MySQL and Postgres, offering automatic scaling, better performance, and lower cost. Deployed as clusters with primary and read replicas.
•	Amazon Redshift: Fully managed data warehouse optimized for online analytical processing (OLAP) and fast SQL queries, supporting concurrency scaling and querying data in S3.
•	NoSQL Databases:

•	Amazon DynamoDB: Fully managed NoSQL database with flexible schema, no table relationships, easy schema updates, and stores data in tables with items and attributes.
•	Amazon DocumentDB: MongoDB-compatible document database storing JSON documents with no rigid schema.

•	In-Memory Databases (Caching):

•	Amazon ElastiCache: Provides caching with sub-millisecond latency using Memcached (simple, multi-threaded, no replication) or Redis (advanced features, replication, high availability).

•	Specialized AWS Databases:

•	Amazon Keyspaces: Managed Apache Cassandra-compatible wide column store.
•	Amazon Neptune: Managed graph database for highly connected data.
•	Amazon Timestream: Serverless time series database for IoT and operational data.
•	Amazon QLDB: Ledger database with immutable, cryptographically verifiable transaction logs.

AWS deployment services:
•	Manual vs Automated Deployment: Manual deployment (copying files, manual server config) is error-prone and slow. AWS offers automated deployment services that speed up provisioning, configuring, updating, and monitoring.

•	Infrastructure as Code (IAC): Managing and provisioning AWS resources using machine-readable definition files (YAML/JSON). This enables one-click deployment of infrastructure.

•	AWS CloudFormation: Primary IAC service that uses templates to define resources (EC2, databases, etc.) deployed as stacks. Supports nested stacks for modular infrastructure. Change sets allow previewing updates before applying. StackSets enable managing stacks across multiple AWS accounts and regions.

•	AWS CDK & SAM: CDK lets you define infrastructure programmatically in languages like Python, Java, TypeScript. SAM extends CloudFormation for easier serverless app development.

•	AWS Elastic Beanstalk: Platform to upload app code (Java, Python, Node.js, Docker, etc.) and automatically deploy and manage the environment. Supports web server and worker environments.

•	AWS CodeDeploy: Automates application deployments to existing compute resources (EC2, ECS, Lambda, on-premises). Does not create resources, only deploys apps.

•	Amazon ECS & EKS: Managed container orchestration for Docker (ECS) and Kubernetes (EKS). Supports deployment on AWS-managed infrastructure, on-premises (ECS Anywhere, EKS Anywhere), or serverless (Fargate).

•	AWS OpsWorks: Configuration management using Chef and Puppet automation for provisioning and managing servers.

•	AWS Proton: Automates container and serverless deployments with pre-approved templates, balancing developer flexibility and platform team control.

•	Scenarios -
Manual vs Automated Deployment: Imagine you manually copy app files to a server and configure it each time you update your app. This is slow and error-prone. Using AWS CodeDeploy automates this process, deploying your app to multiple servers quickly and consistently.

•	Infrastructure as Code with CloudFormation: Suppose you need to set up a web app with servers, databases, and networking. Instead of manually creating each resource, you write a CloudFormation template describing all resources. With one command, AWS provisions everything exactly as defined, saving time and reducing mistakes.

•	Elastic Beanstalk for App Deployment: You have a Python web app. You upload your code to Elastic Beanstalk, and it automatically creates the environment with servers, load balancers, and scaling. You focus on coding while AWS manages the infrastructure.

•	Container Orchestration with ECS/EKS: Your team uses Docker containers for microservices. ECS or EKS manages deploying, scaling, and networking your containers across servers or serverless infrastructure, whether in AWS or on-premises with ECS Anywhere or EKS Anywhere.

•	Hybrid Deployment with ECS Anywhere: Your company has on-premises servers and AWS cloud. ECS Anywhere lets you run and manage container workloads on your own servers, while still using AWS tools for monitoring and scaling.

•	AWS Proton for Large Teams: In a big organization, platform teams create standardized deployment templates with AWS Proton. Developers use these templates to deploy container or serverless apps quickly, ensuring consistency and compliance.

AWS monitoring services:
•	Amazon CloudWatch: Monitors AWS resources and custom applications by collecting metrics and logs.

•	Metrics: Data collected every minute (5 minutes for EC2 by default; detailed monitoring can enable 1-minute intervals).
•	Logs: Collects and stores logs from AWS services and applications via CloudWatch Logs agent.
•	Alarms: Set thresholds on metrics to trigger notifications or actions (e.g., autoscaling, Lambda functions).
•	Events: Responds to system events in near real-time; can trigger actions or scheduled jobs.

Dashboards: Customizable views to monitor resources across regions.
•	AWS Service Health Dashboard: Public dashboard showing status of all AWS services globally.
•	AWS Personal Health Dashboard: Personalized view showing health of AWS services used in your account, including scheduled maintenance and events affecting your resources.
•	AWS Health API: Programmatic access to Personal Health Dashboard data; requires business or enterprise support plan.


Practical Scenarios:
1.	Application Performance Monitoring: Use CloudWatch Metrics and Alarms to monitor CPU usage of your EC2 instances. If CPU usage exceeds 80%, an alarm triggers an autoscaling action to add more instances.
2.	Log Management: Install CloudWatch Logs agent on your application servers to automatically collect logs. Use CloudWatch Logs to analyze errors without logging into each server.
3.	Event-Driven Automation: Create a CloudWatch Event rule to trigger a Lambda function every day at midnight to perform database backups.
4.	Service Health Awareness: Use the AWS Personal Health Dashboard to get alerts about upcoming maintenance that might affect your application, allowing you to plan downtime or mitigation.

AWS auditing and security services 

•	AWS CloudTrail: Tracks user activity and API usage in your AWS account. Logs two types of events:
•	Management Events (control plane): Actions like creating VPCs or attaching IAM roles.
•	Data Events (data plane): Resource-level actions like S3 object access or Lambda invocations.
* CloudTrail logs can be centralized from multiple accounts into one S3 bucket.
•	AWS Artifact: A self-service portal for on-demand AWS security and compliance reports (e.g., ISO, PCI, SOC reports). Useful for verifying AWS compliance standards.
•	AWS Security Hub: Centralizes security alerts and findings from multiple AWS services (GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, etc.) across accounts. Helps maintain compliance with security standards like PCI DSS and CIS benchmarks.

Scenarios:
•	CloudTrail: Imagine you want to audit who created a new VPC or modified IAM roles in your company's AWS environment. CloudTrail logs these management actions so you can review them later.
•	AWS Artifact: Your company needs to prove compliance with PCI standards for a financial project. You use AWS Artifact to download the necessary compliance reports.
•	Security Hub: Your security team wants a single dashboard showing all security alerts from various AWS services across your organization. Security Hub aggregates these alerts to help prioritize and respond.
AWS networking and content delivery services module, along with scenarios to help you understand:

Key Concepts:

•	Amazon VPC: A virtual private network in AWS where you control IP ranges, subnets, and gateways. It isolates your cloud resources and can connect to the internet or on-premises networks via gateways.
•	Elastic Load Balancing (ELB): Distributes incoming traffic across multiple targets (EC2, containers, Lambda) to improve availability and performance. Types include Application Load Balancer (HTTP/HTTPS), Network Load Balancer (TCP/UDP), Gateway Load Balancer (for virtual appliances), and Classic Load Balancer (legacy).
•	Amazon Route 53: DNS service to route domain names to AWS resources like EC2, S3, or load balancers. Supports various routing policies (simple, failover, geolocation, etc.).
•	AWS Global Accelerator: Provides static IP addresses as fixed entry points to multiple AWS regional endpoints, improving global application availability and performance.
•	Amazon CloudFront: Content Delivery Network (CDN) that caches static content at edge locations worldwide for faster delivery.
•	AWS PrivateLink: Enables private connectivity to AWS services without using the public internet, protecting data from interception.
•	AWS VPN: Securely connects your on-premises network to AWS using encrypted tunnels (site-to-site VPN) or client VPN.
•	AWS Direct Connect: Dedicated network connection from your data center to AWS for more consistent and secure connectivity than internet-based VPN.
•	AWS Transit Gateway: Central hub to connect multiple VPCs, VPNs, and Direct Connect gateways, simplifying large network architectures.
•	Amazon API Gateway: Fully managed service to create, publish, and secure RESTful APIs and WebSocket APIs.
•	AWS App Mesh: Service mesh for managing communication between microservices across containers and EC2 instances.
•	AWS Cloud Map: Service discovery for dynamic resources in microservices, enabling applications to find updated resource locations.

Scenarios to Understand Concepts:

•	You launch a web app on multiple EC2 instances in different availability zones. ELB distributes user traffic evenly to ensure no single server is overwhelmed.
•	Your company has an on-premises data center and wants secure, high-speed access to AWS resources. You set up AWS Direct Connect for a dedicated connection and use AWS VPN as backup.
•	You run a global website and use CloudFront to cache images and videos at edge locations near users, reducing load times.
•	Your microservices architecture uses AWS App Mesh to manage communication and monitor traffic between services running in containers.
•	You register your domain with Route 53 and route traffic to an Application Load Balancer that directs requests to your backend servers.

AWS application integration and notification services:

1. Amazon SQS (Simple Queue Service):
•	Managed message queuing service.
•	Two types: Standard (at least once delivery, best effort ordering, higher throughput) and FIFO (exactly once delivery, preserves message order, lower throughput).
•	Used to decouple components by queuing messages for processing by EC2, Lambda, ECS, etc.
•	Supports auto-scaling EC2 instances based on queue metrics.

2. Amazon SNS (Simple Notification Service):
•	Managed pub/sub messaging and notification service.
•	Enables communication between decoupled microservices or direct user notifications (email, SMS, push).
•	Supports message filtering to send specific messages to different subscribers.
•	Can fan out messages to multiple SQS queues or endpoints.

3. AWS Step Functions:
•	Serverless orchestration service for sequencing Lambda functions.
•	Allows building workflows as state machines with visual design.

4. Amazon MQ:
•	Managed message broker service using Apache ActiveMQ.
•	Supports multiple messaging protocols (JMS, AMQP, MQTT, etc.) for compatibility with existing apps.

5. Amazon EventBridge:
•	Serverless event bus for connecting applications and SaaS with AWS services.
•	Supports event ingestion, delivery, security, and error handling.

6. AWS AppSync:
•	Managed GraphQL service for flexible API data queries.
•	Allows querying multiple data sources in a single request.

7. Amazon AppFlow:
•	Managed integration service to securely transfer data between SaaS apps and AWS.
•	Supports data transformation, filtering, and scheduling.

Practical scenarios:
•	Using SQS to queue orders from a web app so backend services process them asynchronously, improving scalability.
•	Using SNS to send alerts to admins via email and SMS when system metrics exceed thresholds.
•	Orchestrating a multi-step image processing workflow with Step Functions, triggering Lambda functions in sequence.
•	Integrating legacy messaging apps with Amazon MQ to migrate to AWS without rewriting protocols.
•	Building event-driven apps with EventBridge to react to changes in SaaS apps or AWS services.
•	Using AppSync to fetch exactly the needed data from multiple APIs in a single client request.
•	Automating data sync between Salesforce and Amazon S3 using AppFlow with filtering and scheduling.

AWS security services:

•	AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall): Protects web apps from common exploits like SQL injection and cross-site scripting by creating custom rules. It can block malicious IPs, limit request rates to reduce DDoS impact, and restrict access by country.
•	AWS Firewall Manager: Centralizes management of WAF rules across multiple AWS accounts and applications, simplifying security rule deployment.
•	AWS Shield: Managed DDoS protection service with two tiers: Standard (free, automatic protection) and Advanced (paid, real-time alerts and support). Protects services like EC2, ELB, CloudFront, and Route 53.
•	Amazon GuardDuty: Threat detection service that monitors for suspicious activities like unusual API calls or compromised instances and sends security findings.
•	AWS CloudHSM: Hardware security module (HSM) for generating and managing encryption keys with exclusive (single-tenant) access within your VPC.
•	AWS Key Management Service (KMS): Managed service for creating and controlling encryption keys using multi-tenant HSMs. Supports automatic key rotation and integrates with many AWS services.
•	AWS Secrets Manager: Manages and rotates secrets like database passwords and API keys securely, avoiding hard-coded sensitive info.
•	AWS Certificate Manager: Creates and manages SSL/TLS certificates for secure communication, including private certificates for internal use.
•	Amazon Macie: Uses machine learning to discover and classify sensitive data (like PII) in S3 buckets, providing dashboards and alerts.
•	Amazon Inspector: Automated security assessment tool that scans applications for vulnerabilities and deviations from best practices.
•	Amazon Detective: Helps investigate and analyze security issues by collecting and analyzing logs from AWS services.


Scenario to understand concepts:
Imagine you deploy a web application on AWS:

•	Use AWS WAF to block common web attacks and restrict access to users from specific countries.
•	Protect your app from DDoS attacks with AWS Shield Standard.
•	Store your app’s database passwords securely with AWS Secrets Manager.
•	Encrypt sensitive data using keys managed by AWS KMS.
•	Monitor for suspicious activity with Amazon GuardDuty and investigate incidents using Amazon Detective.
•	Use AWS Certificate Manager to provision SSL certificates for secure HTTPS communication.

AWS management and governance services:

1. AWS Management Tools:
•	AWS Management Console: Web interface to manage AWS resources securely with multi-factor authentication.
•	AWS CLI: Command-line tool to interact with AWS services, suitable for scripting and automation.
•	AWS Console Mobile App: Monitor resources and metrics on the go, with some limitations compared to the console.
•	AWS Systems Manager (SSM): Suite for managing cloud and on-premises infrastructure, including patching, configuration, automation, and secure parameter storage.
•	AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM): Securely share AWS resources across accounts to reduce duplication and management overhead.

2. AWS Governance Services:
•	AWS Config: Tracks and audits resource configurations to ensure compliance with policies and regulations. Supports automated remediation.
•	AWS Organizations: Centralizes management of multiple AWS accounts, enabling consolidated billing, access control, and policy enforcement via Service Control Policies (SCPs).
•	AWS Service Catalog: Manages approved IT services (products) for deployment, enforcing compliance and access control.
•	AWS Control Tower: Automates setup and governance of multi-account AWS environments with best-practice blueprints and guardrails.


Practical Scenarios:
1.	Compliance Enforcement: A financial services company uses AWS Config to monitor S3 buckets to ensure none are publicly accessible, automatically alerting and remediating violations.
2.	Multi-Account Management: Your organization manages separate AWS accounts for development, testing, and production. AWS Organizations helps centralize billing and enforce security policies across all accounts.
3.	Resource Sharing: Teams in different departments need access to a shared Transit Gateway. AWS RAM allows sharing this resource securely without duplicating it.
4.	Automated Patching: Using AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager, you schedule maintenance windows to automatically patch EC2 instances, reducing manual effort and downtime.

AWS Identity Services module:
•	AWS Identity Services enable secure management of identities, resources, and permissions across AWS and hybrid environments.

AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM):
•	Manages access to AWS services/resources.
•	Create IAM users (with long-term credentials) and groups.
•	Define IAM policies to grant permissions.
•	IAM roles allow users, AWS accounts, or services to assume specific permissions.

1. Amazon Cognito:
•	Adds user sign-up, sign-in, and access control to web/mobile apps.
•	Supports social identity providers (Facebook, Google, Amazon) and enterprise providers (Microsoft AD via SAML).
•	User pools handle authentication (login), identity pools handle authorization (access to AWS resources).

2. AWS Single Sign-On (SSO):

•	Allows one set of credentials to access multiple AWS accounts and business applications.
•	Provides a user portal for easy role access.
•	Integrates with apps like Salesforce, Office 365 via SAML.

AWS Directory Service:
•	Managed Microsoft Active Directory in AWS.
•	No need to replicate or manage domain controllers.
•	Supports assigning IAM roles to AD users/groups and integration with on-premises AD.


Scenarios to understand concepts:
1.	Employee Access Management: Use IAM to create groups for developers and admins, assign policies to control who can launch EC2 instances or access S3 buckets.
2.	Customer App Login: Use Amazon Cognito user pools to let customers sign in with Google or Facebook accounts, and identity pools to grant temporary AWS resource access.
3.	Single Sign-On for Teams: Use AWS SSO so employees log in once and access multiple AWS accounts and apps like Office 365 without multiple passwords.
4.	Hybrid AD Integration: Use AWS Directory Service to extend your company's on-premises Active Directory to AWS, allowing seamless user management and permissions.

